{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UGnxGQGyhEzDVrynTfEVj1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a request to write a test plan for a software engineering issue. I need to analyze each behavior and determine what testing level is needed to catch real failures.\n\nLet me understand the issue:\n- A document analysis system with 3 AI reviewers running in parallel\n- Each reviewer is independent: clause extractor, risk assessor, compliance checker\n- A merge step combines results and resolves conflicts\n- The behaviors describe what should happen at each step\n\nLet me think about the testing levels:\n- **Unit**: single local function/object, no I/O, pure logic\n- **Integration**: multiple modules, local DB/filesystem\n- **System**: subprocess, OS, real HTTP, real external API\n- **Agentic**: depends on real LLM non-determinism or real AI/ML model call\n- **Workflow**: multiple agentic steps in sequence, full pipeline\n\nNow let me analyze each behavior:\n\n### Behavior 1: Clause extractor identifies key terms\n\"The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.\"\n\nQuestions:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this? If we mock the LLM response, we might pass with incomplete extraction. Real LLM might extract differently or more thoroughly.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it need real network/subprocess? Probably calls an LLM API.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking the LLM always pass? Yes - we could mock it to return \"found all terms\" and it would pass.\n- LLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on real LLM? YES - different LLMs extract terms differently. Running the same extraction 100 times might vary slightly (different phrasings detected, etc.)\n\nThis is **Agentic** because:\n- The clause extraction depends on what the real LLM produces\n- Different LLMs or different prompt formulations might extract different clauses\n- Mocking would hide whether the actual LLM can really extract all key terms\n\n\n- A real LLM call is necessary to verify the extractor actually identifies the required term types, catch API integration failures, and detect when the LLM itself fails to extract certain categories. Mocking would mask extraction quality issues and configuration problems with the actual model or endpoint.\n\nThe minimum level needed is **Agentic** - I need to test against a real LLM to confirm the prompt works, the model can perform the task, and the API integration functions correctly. Unit tests with mocks would only catch parsing logic errors. Integration tests might surface some API issues but wouldn't validate the LLM's actual capability. System and workflow tests don't add meaningful coverage for this single extraction step.\n\nFor the risk assessor behavior, a mock could easily miss cases where problematic language appears indirectly or through euphemistic phrasing, since the mock wouldn't actually evaluate the semantic content the way a real model would.  The core challenge is that detecting subtle, indirect risk language depends entirely on real LLM judgment - different models, prompts, or even different runs might catch different edge cases. Only testing with an actual LLM call can verify the prompt and model combination reliably identifies these nuanced risks.\n\nFor the compliance checker, the question is whether it can accurately determine regulatory requirements for a given jurisdiction. A mock would hide whether the real LLM actually understands jurisdiction-specific regulations, and this capability varies significantly across models and their training data. The assessment also hinges on whether the system relies purely on LLM knowledge or needs access to external compliance databases - if it's LLM-only, it's clearly agentic; if it requires real regulatory data sources, the dependency shifts.\n\nGiven the issue mentions \"configured jurisdiction\" without specifying external APIs, I'm treating this as LLM-based with stored jurisdiction configurations, making it **Agentic**. Unit testing can't catch real regulatory knowledge gaps, integration testing is limited without actual LLM evaluation, and system testing would only work if external regulatory sources are involved. Confidence remains low across all levels since mocking obscures the actual capability.\n\nFor the merge step, the three reviewers' outputs can be tested independently—mocking them doesn't hide failures because the merge logic itself is pure computation with no LLM dependency. I can verify it correctly preserves conflicting assessments with attribution by providing test cases where the extractor flags something as \"standard\" while the risk assessor marks it \"high risk\". Integration testing applies here since multiple reviewer outputs need to be wired together, though the actual merging is deterministic and testable in isolation. realistic outputs from actual reviewers. We could mock the reviewer outputs, which would make it Unit.\n\nThe real risk is whether the merge logic correctly detects conflicts and preserves both assessments when outputs have certain formats. To catch this reliably, I need realistic reviewer outputs—either mocked carefully or pulled from actual reviewers.\n\nFor testing the merge logic itself, Unit with mocked outputs should work: construct three reviewer outputs, call merge(), verify it handles conflicts and preserves assessments. Integration becomes necessary only if output format parsing is part of the failure risk.\n\nSince the question focuses on merge logic rather than the reviewers themselves, Unit testing with mocked outputs is sufficient. I can mock the three outputs, pass them through merge, and verify both assessments are preserved.\n\nFor the full pipeline—dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, and merging into a unified report—the situation differs. The question explicitly mentions \"real contract\" and \"without losing any individual reviewer's findings,\" which suggests I need actual reviewer calls rather than mocks. Mocking the reviewers might hide orchestration failures or data loss during collection and merging.\n\nThis is a Workflow test because it involves multiple agentic steps in sequence (three parallel reviewers followed by merge), and I need real LLM calls to verify the pipeline doesn't drop findings. Unit testing can't capture the full orchestration, and while integration testing with mocked LLMs is possible, it would miss real failure modes like timeouts or partial failures.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels: Workflow gets 0.75 since this is the right level for testing the full agentic pipeline, while Agentic gets 0.10 because individual reviewers need to be real but the focus is on orchestration rather than single-step behavior. Subprocess or OS behavior isn't the primary concern here.\n\nI need to structure the output using the StructuredOutput tool with behavior_id, description, minimum_level, justification, test_description, plan_consistent, and level_probabilities. Let me verify my classifications are accurate—for Clause Extraction, the minimum level should be Agentic since I need to verify the real LLM can extract all required clause types from contracts; mocking would mask extraction quality issues. The test involves running the real clause extractor on diverse contracts to verify all key term types like parties, dates, obligations, and penalties are captured consistently. Risk Assessment also requires Agentic level because detecting indirect or euphemistic risk language depends on actual LLM judgment—different models or prompts might miss subtle risks that mocking would hide. I'd test this by running the real risk assessor on contracts with subtle, indirect risk language to ensure high-risk items get flagged even when not explicit. Compliance Checking appears to need Agentic level as well, though I'm still evaluating this one.\n\nRegulatory compliance checking relies on the LLM understanding jurisdiction-specific requirements, and different models have varying knowledge bases. I'd test the real compliance checker on contracts known to be compliant or non-compliant across various jurisdictions, verifying correct determinations and testing edge cases near regulatory boundaries. Merge with Conflict Preservation is different—this is a pure function that can work with mocked reviewer outputs, so Unit level testing suffices. I'd create test cases with mocked outputs from three reviewers including disagreements on the same clause, then verify the merge preserves both assessments with clear attribution to each source.\n\nThe full pipeline requires Workflow level testing since it orchestrates three parallel reviewers plus merge with real LLM calls on actual contracts. End-to-end execution catches orchestration failures and data loss that unit tests miss. I'd run it on diverse contracts with varying complexity and reviewer disagreement patterns to ensure all three results are collected and the merged report contains findings from all reviewers.\n\nReconsidering the compliance behavior though—the issue mentions \"configured jurisdiction,\" which could indicate jurisdiction data is loaded from a config file or database rather than relying solely on the LLM's knowledge. If requirements are stored locally, that shifts it toward Integration level. If the LLM is expected to know the regulations itself, it stays Agentic.\n\nThe core question is whether the LLM correctly interprets contract terms against those requirements. Configuration is just input data, so the real test is the LLM's interpretation capability. I'll classify both behaviors as Agentic since they require the LLM to detect subtle risks and verify compliance, even though jurisdiction requirements are configured. The compliance check might decompose into field extraction, checklist matching, and logic, but the issue description emphasizes determining whether the contract meets regulatory requirements—suggesting the LLM needs to do more than simple matching.\n\nFor the probability distributions, behavior 1 needs a real LLM to verify extraction quality, so Agentic dominates at 0.95 with a small Workflow probability of 0.05. Behavior 2 similarly requires the LLM to detect subtle language patterns against policy, making mocking insufficient.\n\nBehavior 3 is trickier—compliance checking could range from simple checklist matching (Unit level) to requiring external regulatory APIs (System level) or genuine LLM reasoning about regulations (Agentic level). The key question is whether a real failure means the LLM misunderstands compliance rules or just fails to apply a known checklist correctly.\n\nIf the LLM needs to interpret contracts against jurisdiction-specific regulations, that's fundamentally an Agentic problem. External API failures or misconfigured data would point to System or Integration issues instead. Given the ambiguity about what \"configured\" means here, I'm treating this as requiring LLM judgment, so Agentic gets the highest weight at 0.60, with System at 0.20 for potential external dependencies, Integration at 0.15, and minimal Unit/Workflow allocation.\n\nFor each behavior, the minimum test level depends on whether real LLMs are involved. The three individual reviewers all require Agentic-level testing since mocking them would mask actual LLM failures. The merge logic itself is pure code and can be tested at Unit level with mocked inputs, unless it involves complex format parsing. The full pipeline needs Workflow-level testing to verify end-to-end behavior with real contracts. The critical detail is that \"without losing any individual reviewer's findings\" refers to orchestration and data collection across components—this demands Integration or Workflow level to ensure results aren't dropped during merging, not just Unit-level logic verification. result.clause_extractor_findings is not None\n    assert result.risk_assessor_findings is not None\n    assert result.compliance_checker_findings is not None\n    \n    # Verify findings are merged correctly\n    assert len(result.merged_assessments) > 0\n    assert all(assessment.has_multiple_perspectives for assessment in result.merged_assessments)\n```\n\nThis is Integration because it requires all three real LLMs working together end-to-end.\n\nThe key insight is that the test type depends on what's actually being called: if real external services are involved, it's Agentic or Integration; if only internal logic is tested with mocks, it's Unit. two reviewers have identical findings and the merge silently drops duplicates → Unit-level test catches this if we construct the right test case\n\nSo actually, all the failure modes for merge can be caught at Unit level with proper test construction. We don't need Integration or Agentic to test the merge function itself.\n\nBut wait - the original test I wrote was Integration level because it runs the full pipeline with real LLMs. That's testing the entire workflow end-to-end, not just the merge function in isolation.\n\nLet me reconsider the behavior probabilities. For the merge function specifically:\n- Unit: 0.85 (construct mock reviewer outputs, verify merge logic)\n- Integration: 0.10 (run real reviewers, merge their outputs, verify result)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (test merge within full agent workflow)\n\nActually, I should adjust behavior 4 to reflect this. The merge function can be thoroughly tested at Unit level, so that should be the dominant approach. which might vary). Unit testing with manually constructed outputs is sufficient if the structure is straightforward, but Integration becomes valuable if real reviewer formatting introduces complexity.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm settling on Unit as the baseline (0.70) since the merge logic itself is testable with well-defined inputs, Integration at (0.25) for cases where output format parsing matters, and minimal weight on Workflow (0.05).\n\nBehavior 5 requires a different approach entirely. The description emphasizes the complete end-to-end flow—dispatching across all three reviewers, aggregating their results, and consolidating findings into one report. Using an actual contract document rather than synthetic inputs, combined with multiple reviewer agents operating in sequence, points toward Workflow testing. The critical validation here is ensuring no individual assessment gets dropped during collection or merging.\n\nI can't adequately test this at Unit level since the full orchestration can't be isolated. Integration with mocked reviewers also falls short because the description specifically calls for real contract handling and realistic reviewer outputs. Workflow is the appropriate fit—it exercises the actual agentic steps and verifies the pipeline preserves all findings end-to-end.\n\nMy final assessment for Behavior 5: Unit (0.0), Integration (0.0), System (0.05), Agentic (0.15), Workflow (0.80). or a full agent pipeline. Behavior 5 is the complete orchestration—dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting their results, and merging them into a unified report. This matches the \"full agent pipeline\" definition exactly, so Workflow is the right level. The test would invoke the real clause extractor, risk assessor, and compliance checker in sequence, then verify that all findings are preserved through the merge step. I'm confident Workflow is appropriate here. Now I need to finalize the test descriptions, making sure each one is at least 10 characters and clearly shows what's being tested. I need to structure the output now with the test behaviors defined and validated.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13415,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13415},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent